post_text:
Like all school districts, Deer Lakes takes many photographs of its students and staff every single day and uses them in a variety of ways including: social media, website, district publications, outside publications, television broadcasts, etc.

For most families, this is perfectly acceptable and can be exciting. However, there are occasions where people do not want their child photographed under any circumstances and we need to know that information as well so that we can honor everyone’s stated preferences.

If you find yourself in the latter group and you absolutely DO NOT want your child’s photo publicly disseminated for any reason, please check the appropriate box indicating your disapproval in your child’s Skyward account.

If you are fine with your child’s photo being taken and used in various ways to promote Deer Lakes, simply disregard that section.

Please send any questions you may have to backtoschool@deerlakes.net.

post_text:
Pennsylvania’s Children’s Health Insurance Program (CHIP) covers uninsured children and teens up to age 19 — and no family earns too much to qualify.

CHIP provides quality, comprehensive health insurance for routine doctor visits, prescriptions, dental, eye care, eyeglasses, mental health, and more.

CHIP covers uninsured kids who are ineligible for medical assistance. For most families, CHIP is free — for others it is low cost.

The formal registration period for Deer Lakes’ Healthy & Safe Return to School plan is now open for district families. You may register your child for any of our three learning tracks on a desktop, laptop, or mobile device using any major browser, including Google Chrome and Safari, amongst others.

Please note that the form is unavailable through our district app and all submissions must be made through a parent Skyward account, not a student’s account. Visit your Skyward account for
step-by-step directions for how to register your child for any of our three learning tracks.

Parents will have the opportunity to engage with the district’s administrative team on a Q&A at 6 p.m., on Monday, Aug. 10. Visit the district’s website for more information. The formal registration
period closes for all Deer Lakes families at 11:59 p.m. on Tuesday, Aug. 11.

Deer Lakes will hold a virtual Q&A forum for district families at 6 p.m., on Monday, Aug. 10, so that everyone can be sure they are making the best decision possible for their child’s education.

Students or parents wishing to ask questions may submit them via the Zoom meeting's chat function.

District personnel will read the question aloud before answering it. Also, students and parents looking for answers may also submit questions to the district's dedicated email address: backtoschool@deerlakes.net. We regularly monitor the account and are posting reponses to those questions here.

The district will not address any personnel-related issues during the meeting. Should you have any questions highly specific to your situation, please reach out to your child's principal.

Formal registration for our various learning tracks will open on Friday, Aug. 7 and will close on Tuesday, Aug. 11 at 11:59 p.m.

No appointment is necessary to attend, but guests will be expected to comply with all county and state safety mandates, which includes wearing a mask at all times while in Deer Lakes facilities and maintaining social distancing protocols.

Also, to ensure that we are complying with all local and state mandates, guests will be asked to wait outside until a representative from the school escorts them into the auditorium.

#DLProud

• ANY SPECIAL REQUESTS MUST BE MADE THROUGH THE ONLINE SYSTEM

As school districts across the Commonwealth look to reopen their buildings for the 2020-2021 school year, Deer Lakes has formed a Pandemic Team to develop plans and options for returning to school in the fall, following all applicable CDC and Pennsylvania Department of Education guidelines.

Please help us learn from your experiences during the spring 2020 remote learning period by completing the attached survey so that we might better serve our students going forward. Also, please note that while all feedback will be considered and is very much appreciated, some of the suggestions made may not be feasible or implemented. As our plans continue to evolve and draw into a sharper focus, you will have more opportunities to provide us with feedback on all manner of issues.

Kindly, fill out one survey per household to give us a better picture of our families’ perspective across various grade levels. As time is of the essence, surveys should be completed by no later than Thursday, June 18.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeRFljUcHj6AA80TLKdhuOcooG1QR1MGWvw6ViHKkqU0iXVPA/viewform

One of the great traditions Deer Lakes has implemented in recent years has been the annual Senior Walk, where graduating students get to walk through their old stomping grounds one final time to bid farewell to their current and former mentors.

Unfortunately, this year's Senior Walk never happened because our buildings have been closed since March. However, great traditions must live on and if the students couldn't visit their teachers and staff, the teachers and staff were happy to send their messages of encouragement virtually to the Deer Lakes High School Graduating Class of 2020.

Well done and good luck!

#DLTogether
#DLHS2020
#Lancers4Life
#DLProud

Every school day for the past month, we have recognized our graduating seniors through a program with have called the Senior Spotlight.￼

The features have outlined our students’ many wonderful achievements, their preferences, their immediate plans and of course their dreams.￼

Today is the last scheduled day for Senior Spotlight recognition. Thank you to the 91 students who chose to participate in the program.

Also, if your son or daughter has not been recognized but you still wish for them to be recognized, we would still be happy to do that.

Please complete ￼￼the form the high school student council sent out last month and submit it by Wednesday of next week. Any submissions received after Wednesday, May 27, 2020 will not be featured.￼
#DLTogether

Penn State is offering STEM Virtual Camps this Summer for Young Scientists ages 4-14 years:

Summer will look a little different this year but the Discovery Space model of providing fun and engaging STEM experiences remains unchanged! Discovery Space is offering kits full of activities and experiments for week-long explorations of science themes, from ocean diversity to biomedical engineering, and for scientists from ages 4-14 years. We’ll provide all the materials, video and written resources, as well as the option to come together for interactive online sessions to share progress, ask questions, and play games! Find all the details and register below.

https://bit.ly/364m8B9

Today, Curtisville Primary Center wellness instructor, Ron Nichols introduced his students to a lesson he called "Creative Movement." Nichols, with the help of his family, created a drum circle to get his students moving and dancing for physical fitness.

The lesson encouraged students to watch the video a few times to learn the beat and to clap along with it. Then, with their parents' permission, they could use their creativity to join in by creating a makeshift drum kit of their own and join the online drum circle.

post_text:
This Saturday, ￼￼West Deer residents are holding ￼a parade for ALL graduating seniors in the district, including students who attend Deer Lakes or a private school as well as recent college grads.

This is not a Deer Lakes School District sponsored event but we certainly support it. ￼￼

The parade will start at the Cedar Ridge Plan. Seniors will line up starting at 4:30 p.m. at Cedar Glen Road behind the fire truck/police car facing the cul-de-sac at the end of Cedar Glen. The parade will be led by WDPD and WDFD.

Seniors, please dress in either your Deer Lakes or future college colors. Please have a sign with your name and any other information you want to provide.

Decorate your cars!

Residents, please come out to cheer on the seniors. Decorate your yards and make some noise!

Proudly wear your DL colors!

Visitors are also invited to visit the plans and cheer on the seniors.

Please either park in a friend/neighbors drive way or on the same side of the street to allow for easy access for the “marchers”.

Please remember to practice all social distancing rules!

#DLProud
#DLTogether

Earlier today, the Pennsylvania Department of Education announced the mandatory closure of schools throughout the Commonwealth for the remainder of the 2019-2020 academic year.

Though the news was not entirely unexpected, the timing of it was, as the agency did not give schools any prior notice that such an important announcement was forthcoming. As such, we are still working through the details of what today's decision means for Deer Lakes and how to best proceed going forward.

We are all also currently under a shelter in place order from Governor Wolf. We will continue to follow the guidance we receive from local, state and federal authorities for when it is safe to resume normal activities. We appreciate your patience as we work through a long list of issues including graduation, prom, retrieval of personal possessions, etc.

Please continue to check your Skyward account in the coming days and weeks ahead for the most up-to-date information on Deer Lakes' plans going forward.

#DLTogether

Hello, Deer Lakes community!

The COVID-19 pandemic has been awful on a lot of fronts. However, if there is a silver lining, it is that it has caused our families and our entire community to pull together even more than usual.

Going forward, starting today and as part of Throwback Thursday (#TBT), our staff has decided to participate in a game we are calling Yesteryearbook (#DLYesteryearbook).

How many people can you name?

Here’s how the game works:

In the morning, we will issue a page with nine images of people you may know.

Around lunchtime, we will issue an updated page which includes their respective alma maters and graduation years.

Finally, at around 2 PM, we will issue the full reveal. Whoever gets the most correct names the fastest wins!

Without further ado, here are today’s subjects.
#TBT
#DLYesteryearbook

The Deer Lakes High School Student Council is currently holding its annual elections for the 2020-2021 school year.

All nominees MUST have previously held an office in the council for AT LEAST one year, or have experience as a homeroom representative, class senator, or as a member of the executive board.

Only current juniors are eligible for the board's presidency. Eligible individuals are permitted to be self-nominated only once. The nomination deadline is April 8 with Election Day scheduled for April 15.

Elected officials will shadow current officials for the month of May. The incoming members of the Executive Board will begin their one-year term upon the graduation of the Class of 2020.

Interested students should contact sponsor, Mrs. Mary DeLuca mdeluca@deerlakes.net, class president, Alyson Frank, frank@deerlakes.net, or school board representative, Jacob Kozlowski, jkozlowski@deerlakes.net.

The COVID-19 pandemic has had a profound impact on our district calendar. Today, in consultation with the high school student council, Deer Lakes announced that it is postponing its annual high school prom, which had been scheduled for May 22 at the DoubleTree Hilton Hotel Pittsburgh-Cranberry.

The high school administrators, event organizers and the student council are jointly working on a replacement event, which would likely be held over the summer after the public safety measures have been relaxed. However, those talks are still very much in the planning stage.

Starting Monday, March 30, Deer Lakes will offer free grab-&-go meals twice per week to district families in need of food during this incredibly difficult time. The meals, which can be picked up on Mondays or Wednesdays from 9-11 a.m., are completely free regardless of your financial circumstance or whether or not you have children in our schools.

Also, please remain in your car while picking up food for your loved ones. Our trained and protected staff members will happily bring the food out to you.

In the meantime, please remember that #WeGotThis, so please whenever you can, Stay Calm. Stay Home. Stay Safe.

#DLStrong

Unfortunately, we are in the midst of a once-in-a-lifetime event and schools all across the country have been forced to offer remote instruction or no instruction at all.

Deer Lakes is fortunate to be able to offer remote instruction to all of its students, each of whom has his or her own personal learning device.

Starting tomorrow, we would like to see photos from our students and their families, as well as our staff, to show what their new makeshift classrooms look like -- warts and all.

We would like you to include your smiling faces as well as your classmates, both of the two and four-legged variety.

So, please tag all of your photos with #DLRemoteLearning.

post_text:
The Allegheny County Health Department today confirmed 40 positives cases of COVID-19, with four individuals hospitalized. The department is also aware of a number of additional cases that have not yet been updated in the system and expects these numbers to continue to grow.

The most important thing you can do to help stop the spread is to stay at home and practice social distancing. What the community is doing today has an impact next week and the week after that so please stay on target. Stay home and continue social distancing. Continue to practice good hygiene. Wash your hands often. Cover your coughs and sneezes. Frequently clean highly-touched surfaces.

If you are sick, stay at home. Remain separated from others so as not to further spread any virus or disease.

And visit www.alleghenycounty.us/coronavirus for important information and tools to help you through this, including CDC’s self-checker.

March 19 at 10:53 AM ·

Dear A.W. Beattie Families,

This is the fourth update to the Career Center website and our social media accounts. As events change within the region, we will continue to provide updates related to events at A.W. Beattie.

At this time, Career Center instructors will begin reaching out to their students through their A.W. Beattie email accounts to provide electronic engagement/enrichment to curriculum material that has been covered in the classroom. No new material will be introduced, but this may change as we move forward. As of March 18, the Career Center is closed to students. The electronic engagement/enrichment curriculum offered to students will not require them to gain access to materials at the Career Center.

Click here for more information on how students login to their emails: https://www.beattietech.com/Content/162

The Project Prom Gown Giveaway provides free, new or gently used, gowns and formal accessories to students who may otherwise have to miss the prom because of the cost. Any student who receives services from the Allegheny County Department of Human Services (DHS) or qualifies for a free or reduced school lunch is eligible for Project Prom.

Project Prom is located at Thriftique in Lawrenceville, 125 51st Street, Pittsburgh PA 15201.

Students can visit the Thriftique Project Prom Shop to select their gowns on the following dates and times:

Saturday, March 21 – 10:00 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.
Sunday, March 22 – 10:00 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.
Monday, March 23 – 3:00 p.m. to 6:30 p.m.
Thursday, March 26 – 3:00 p.m. to 6:30 p.m.
Saturday, March 28 – 10:00 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.

Transportation
Free onsite parking is available. Students can also take Port Authority bus routes 87, 91 or 93 to 51st/Stanton and Butler Streets.

Earlier today, John White(CVS/Caremark), Dave Piontek (Goodwill of Southwestern Pennsylvania Industries), Marie Pelloni (FortyX80) and Claire Guth (University of Pittsburgh-Swanson School of Engineering) visited Deer Lakes Middle School, where they shadowed and mentored some of our students as part of an initiative called "Companies in the Classroom."

The goal of the day, which was put together by Consortium for Public Education, was to begin to build a relationship between the school district and some of these local businesses. It also was an opportunity for Deer Lakes Middle School to showcase what they are doing to prepare students for their futures.

Our guests talked about their personal histories and the opportunities their organizations can share/offer to students so that they may better understand career options, pathways and what companies may look for when hiring, etc.

#DLProud

The Deer Lakes team of (from left) Marlee Bieniek, Giovanni Vergerio, Rylee Maruski, and Ellie Miller — all fourth graders at East Union Intermediate Center — ￼outdueled 30 other elementary teams to take first place in the Grades 4-5 division at the K’Nex STEM Design Challenge, funded by Thermo Fisher Scientific.

Teams of students participated in a two-hour competition where they designed, developed and implemented a solution to an engineering problem.

Each new team received a free K'Nex kit to help build their projects.

As the winning team, the Deer Lakes students will represent Pittsburgh in the Grades 4-5 division ￼in the state competition being held at Harrisburg University on May 19, 2020.

Also, Deer Lakes’ Middle School team of ￼(from left) Lia DeForce-Petersen, Natalie Shaffer, Jillian Bieber, and Eva Stotler — all seventh graders — placed third out of 40 teams in the Grades 7-8 division of the competition. ￼
#DLProud

post_text:
Yesterday, students in Mrs. Desiree Rotondo‘s French classes celebrated Mardi Gras.

The holiday is French for "Fat Tuesday," and also called Shrove Tuesday. It is celebrated in most French speaking nations and territories, most famously, in Louisiana in the United States. It is always celebrated on the day before Ash Wednesday, which marks the start of Christian Lent season leading up to Easter.

During Lent, many Christians fast, and the name Fat Tuesday refers to the last day of eating richer foods before the leaner days of Lent begin.

Annie will also compete in baton twirling at the Arnold Sports Games in Columbus, Ohio March 7, 2020. The winner will earn a $5,000 scholarship.

#DLProud
